        ", where he later opened a school for children.     In 1905 he won a Nobel Prize for his lifetime achievements as an epic writer. In his acceptance speech, he said this honor was of particular value to a son of Poland: She was pronounced dead — yet here is proof that she lives on.... She was pronounced defeated — and here is proof that she is victorious.      His social and political activities resulted in a diminished literary output. He wrote a new historical novel, Na polu chwały , that was meant as the beginning of a new trilogy; it was, however, criticized as being a lesser version of his original ": null
